<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a creditor repossess my car during bankruptcy?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not without court permission. The automatic stay under 11 U.S.C. Section 362 prohibits any act to obtain possession of property of the estate. A creditor who wants to repossess collateral during bankruptcy must file a motion for relief from stay and get a court order before taking any action. Repossession without court order is a stay violation."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a motion for relief from stay?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A motion for relief from stay (MFRS) is a formal request by a creditor asking the bankruptcy court to lift the automatic stay for a specific debt or piece of property. The creditor must file the motion, serve it on the debtor and trustee, and the court holds a hearing. Until the court grants the motion, the creditor cannot take any collection action."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should I do if a creditor repossesses my property without a court order?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Document everything immediately: date, time, location, who took the property, any witnesses. Contact your attorney to file an emergency motion for contempt and turnover (return of property). File a police report. File a complaint with the CFPB. For individual debtors, Section 362(k) provides for actual damages, costs, attorney fees, and punitive damages for willful stay violations."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What damages can I recover for an automatic stay violation?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under Section 362(k), individual debtors can recover actual damages (including emotional distress in some circuits), costs and attorney fees, and in appropriate circumstances, punitive damages. For corporate debtors, the court can impose sanctions under Section 105(a). Some industry-wide settlements for systemic stay violations have exceeded $788 million."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How common are unauthorized repossessions during bankruptcy?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Unauthorized repossessions occur more frequently than most people realize. Some creditors have systemically sent repossession agents to properties during active bankruptcies without first obtaining court orders. Large auto lenders have been subject to regulatory enforcement actions and class action settlements for patterns of stay violations."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>
